column14:
NASA will host a one-day event for 20 of its social media followers on March 10, 2013, as part of the week-long 2013 SXSW® Interactive Festival in Austin, Texas. The SXSW Interactive Festival features five days of compelling presentations from the brightest minds in emerging technology, scores of exciting networking events hosted by industry leaders, the SXSW Trade Show and a lineup of special programs showcasing the best new digital works, video games and innovative ideas the international community has to offer.


Participants will get special one-day access to NASA’s SXSW interactive panels and hear from and meet NASA scientists, engineers, astronauts, managers and the folks behind the agency’s social media efforts.


NASA Social participants will have the opportunity to:

  • Take part on Sunday, March 10, in one of the most energetic, inspiring and creative events of the year.
  • Learn about NASA’s James Webb Space Telescope, the most ambitious telescope ever constructed. Hubble’s tennis court-sized successor will be 100 times more powerful and orbit far beyond Earth’s Moon, where it will beam back images of the universe’s first galaxies as well as celestial objects hidden by clouds of cosmic dust.
  • View the full-sized Webb telescope model outdoors, and then get an in-depth look at the perplexing questions the telescope is designed to answer: How did the universe form? Is our solar system unique? Are we alone in the cosmos?
  • Visit the NASA Experience Tent, filled with displays, videos, multimedia products and hands-on activities. As part of the NASA tent, Microsoft Research will be running their World Wide Telescope on a 10’x20’ visualization wall that lets users fly through the universe and explore planets, stars, etc.
  • Join Astronaut Ron Garan and others from NASA to socialize and discuss the latest innovations in space technology. Mingle with the pros and exchange stories about your favorite space mission.
  • Meet the people behind NASA’s Mars Curiosity landing social media campaign, see what helped NASA capture the public's attention and what's in store for the mission.
  • Meet NASA designers who want to share a little about the history of the user experience in space, check out state-of-the-art tools aboard the space station and learn how to use free online tools to engage with NASA missions.
  • Attend a star party with speakers ranging from astrophysicists to astronauts to Nobel laureates.

For more information about the SXSW Interactive Festival, visit: http://sxsw.com/interactive

What is a NASA Social?
A NASA Social is an informal meeting of people who use social networking sites such as Twitter, Facebook and Google+. Participants at this event will be provided a unique NASA in-person experience at SXSW, which they are encouraged to share with others through their favorite social network.


Guests will have an opportunity to see a life-sized model of the world's largest space telescope, NASA's James Webb Space Telescope, along with bigger-than-life exhibits, educational events, interactives, visualizations, scientists and much more at the South by Southwest (SXSW®) Festival. The NASA Social at SXSW® will be free. Registration badges are required for access to the SXSW Conference, Festival and Trade Show events. For more information about the festival, visit:http://sxsw.com/interactive


How do I register?
Registration opens at 10 a.m. EST on Tuesday, Feb. 19, 2013, and closes at 5 p.m. EST Thursday, Feb. 21. Participants will be randomly selected from qualified online registrations. Registration is for one person only (you) and is non-transferable.
Additional registrants will be placed on a waiting list.


Do I need to have a social media account to register?
Yes. This event is designed for active social media users who follow NASA on Twitter (@NASA, @NASASocial), Facebook (NASA) or Google+ (NASA). The goal of NASA Social is to allow people who regularly interact with each other via social networks to meet in person and discuss science and exploration.

Users on all social networks are encouraged to use the hashtags #NASASXSW and #NASASocial. Updates and information about the event will be shared on Twitter via @NASASocial and via posts to Facebook and Google+.

If you are not a regular user of social media and just want to learn more about NASA, we offer other ways to connect with us. You can begin at www.nasa.gov

...

Some events and participants scheduled to appear at the event are subject to change without notice. NASA and SXSW are not responsible for loss or damage incurred as a result of attending. NASA and SXSW, moreover, are not responsible for loss or damage incurred if the event is cancelled with limited or no notice. Please plan accordingly.

NASA has made special guest access arrangements for the participants of the NASA Social. To attend other sessions or parts of the event, you must register separately for SXSW.

Can I register if I am not a U.S. citizen?
Yes.

Does my registration include a guest?
Because of space limitations, you may not bring a guest. Each registration provides a place for one person only (you) and is non-transferable. Each individual wishing to attend must register separately.


When will I know if I am selected?
After registrations have been received and processed, an email with confirmation information and additional instructions will be sent to those selected and those on the waitlist. We expect to send notifications no later than Tuesday, Feb. 26.


Does registration for and/or attendance at the NASA Social qualify me for media accreditation?
Your NASA Social registration and/or attendance does not qualify you for news media credentials now or in the future.


Need more information? Help is available by sending an email to HQ-Social@mail.nasa.gov.



Details via nasa.gov

column14:
Pub Crawl + Pub Run...


Fit Approach & Rogue Runners have teamed up to create a fun, athletic event for SX-goers and local Austinites to get together, get sweaty and visit some local watering holes. Join us for a Sunday fun-day and explore the city one pub at a time!


We’ll be meeting at Rogue Runners at 11:00 am, and from there — jogging, skipping, socializing, and hopefully not stumbling — to four different pub locations throughout the city. We’ll end up right back where we started, at Rogue Runners, where we’ll have a fun reception with a recovery station and fun raffles to wrap up the day!


Whether you’re in it for the excercise, camaraderie, booze — or all the above — we can’t think of a better way to spend our Sunday during SX!


Meeting location: Rogue Running, (500 San Marcos St., Austin, TX) — we’ll hit the road to start our run around 11:30am and we’ll be making stops at the following pubs:


  • 1st stop: Yellow Jacket Social Club, 11:50-12:25
  • 2nd stop: The Side Bar, 12:50-1:25
  • 3rd stop: Brew Exchange, 1:45-2:20
  • 4th stop: Banger’s Sausage and Beer Garden, 2:45-3:25


We’ll arrive back at Rogue Runners at 3:45 for a fun reception and recovery station provided by Zola Coconut Water + Swag & Goodies...


*Bring cash for each bar, your I.D., and your party pants!


via Facebook

column2: Fast Company Happy Hour (Day Two)
column13: Fast Company, in association with the BMF Media Group, will host the Fast Company Grill in Austin, Texas from March 8-12, 2013. The FastCompany Grill will feature an exclusive five-day restaurant, lounge, and arcade exclusive to artists, celebrities, media, VIPs and tastemakers. The Fast Company Grill will showcase exciting interactive activities daily from sponsors Lincoln, Target, Starbucks Doubleshot, and Evite. Through the selection of key Austin partners, The Lincoln Hello, Again experience will re-imagine the space into a blend of the city, through gaming and interactive technology. FastCompany will be interviewing top business, technology and media executives including Jonah Peretti, Jared Leto, Kevin Rose, Dennis Crowley, Troy Carter, Doug Ulman and Padma Warrior for its “Creative Conversations” video series. Fast Company aims to reveal the inner thoughts and ideas of unlikely business pairings as they share how they innovate and re-imagine their companies, products, media and technology with one another. Target and Fast Company are celebrating their first-ever partnership at the Fast Company Grill with four dedicated Happy Hours featuring notable co-hosts Cultivated Wit with Baratunde Thurston and Girls In Tech, along with a special performance by Glenn Tilbrook of Squeeze on Friday. Target is transforming a section of the Fast Company Grill to a “Tarcade” with refurbished retro video games, Minneapolis inspired cocktails, NFC Tarcade cards, and opportunities for guests to challenge each other throughout the week. Fast Company Grill visitors will be asked to Power The Morning by Starbucks Doubleshot over daily complimentary breakfasts and premium Doubleshot beverages. Breakfasts will feature content sessions and book giveaways, with Fast Future: How the Millennial Generation Is Shaping Our World and Change Generation writer/author David Burstein. The Fast Company Grill will showcase exciting interactive activities daily from sponsors Lincoln, Target, Starbucks Doubleshot, and Evite.

Through the selection of key Austin partners, The Lincoln Hello, Again experience will re-imagine the space into a blend of the city, through gaming and interactive technology. FastCompany will be interviewing top business, technology and media executives including Jonah Peretti, Jared Leto, Kevin Rose, Dennis Crowley, Troy Carter, Doug Ulman and Padma Warrior for its “Creative Conversations” video series. Fast Company aims to reveal the inner thoughts and ideas of unlikely business pairings as they share how they innovate and re-imagine their companies, products, media and technology with one another.

column2: IEEE/W3C Open Future Meetup with Tim Berners-Lee
column13: You’re invited to join the IEEE and W3C Open Future Series speakers along with special guest, Tim Berners-Lee. Enjoy the ambience at the Driskill Hotel as you learn more about ways to get involved on the bleeding edge of web and technology development. Meet our world renown panelists and speakers and engage in dialog about the Open Web Platform, Internet of Things, HTML5, Web Privacy, Augmented Reality, Cloud Computing, Green Tech, Sensor Networking and more. You’ll learn more about W3C’s Web Platform Docs, a community-driven site launched by W3C that aims to become a comprehensive and authoritative source for web developer documentation. You’ll also discover OpenStand, a jointly supported, global community advocating for the open web and open standards. Sponsored by IEEE.

column2: Cory Booker: The New Media Politician (Badges / Wristbands)
column5: The Long Center for the Performing Arts (Dell Hall)
column13: A Conversation between Mayor Cory Booker and Steven James Snyder of TIME |Few politicians use social media as openly, or prolifically, as Cory Booker. As the mayor of Newark, New Jersey, he has used his personal Twitter feed to interact with constituents on an hourly basis; to follow @CoryBooker is to understand the daily challenge of leading one of America’s largest cities. The mayor is routinely responding to questions and complaints – about issues ranging from potholes to snowdrifts and neighborhood violence. When not personally investigating an issue, he forwards phone numbers and e-mail addresses to his followers, directing residents to various city agencies. He endorses city businesses, shares inspirational quotes, responds directly to tweets of joy or frustration from his followers – and just last night shared his unabashed love for all things “Star Trek.”|In an age of media advisors, pollsters and strategists, when most politicians appear only in carefully scripted settings, Mayor Booker has used Twitter to defy the norm, opening himself up to candid, continuous (and some might say relentless) contact with those he governs. In 2012, he also aggressively used his social feeds to respond to the fallout of Superstorm Sandy, which left New Jersey in a state of emergency, and used his personal Twitter feed to offer hourly updates on his widely-publicized week-long Food Stamp Challenge.|What has Mayor Booker learned about his community through their RT’s and DM’s? Have his online interactions led to shifts in policy or priorities? How does he see social media reshaping what it means to lead and govern in the 21st century? Alternatively, does he see any risks, in becoming so engaged with residents who tweet that he loses sight of the citizens without a Twitter handle?|And as the mayor considers a 2014 senate bid, does he believe that a Senator Booker could be every bit as open and candid via social media as Mayor Booker has been?|via SX Interactive
column14:
A Conversation between Mayor Cory Booker and Steven James Snyder of TIME



Few politicians use social media as openly, or prolifically, as Cory Booker. As the mayor of Newark, New Jersey, he has used his personal Twitter feed to interact with constituents on an hourly basis; to follow @CoryBooker is to understand the daily challenge of leading one of America’s largest cities. The mayor is routinely responding to questions and complaints – about issues ranging from potholes to snowdrifts and neighborhood violence. When not personally investigating an issue, he forwards phone numbers and e-mail addresses to his followers, directing residents to various city agencies. He endorses city businesses, shares inspirational quotes, responds directly to tweets of joy or frustration from his followers – and just last night shared his unabashed love for all things “Star Trek.”


In an age of media advisors, pollsters and strategists, when most politicians appear only in carefully scripted settings, Mayor Booker has used Twitter to defy the norm, opening himself up to candid, continuous (and some might say relentless) contact with those he governs. In 2012, he also aggressively used his social feeds to respond to the fallout of Superstorm Sandy, which left New Jersey in a state of emergency, and used his personal Twitter feed to offer hourly updates on his widely-publicized week-long Food Stamp Challenge.


What has Mayor Booker learned about his community through their RT’s and DM’s? Have his online interactions led to shifts in policy or priorities? How does he see social media reshaping what it means to lead and govern in the 21st century? Alternatively, does he see any risks, in becoming so engaged with residents who tweet that he loses sight of the citizens without a Twitter handle?


And as the mayor considers a 2014 senate bid, does he believe that a Senator Booker could be every bit as open and candid via social media as Mayor Booker has been?


via SX Interactive

column2: Grass Hill Entertainment and Parks Arts present Walter Parks and Swamp Cabbage
column12: Walter Parks & Swamp Cabbage
column13: Humorously christened "the best band nobody's ever heard of" by fans on their recent tour of Spain, this trio is nonetheless engorged with marquee value. For 10 years, bandleader Walter Parks was sideman to Woodstock legend Richie Havens playing Madison Square Garden and Carnegie Hall. Bassist Jim Devito recorded all of JJ Grey and Mofro's fine albums. Drummer Jagoda played on T Bone Burnett's recent record Tooth of Crime. If you like early ZZ TOP, THE METERS, DR JOHN, TOM WAITS, TONY JOE WHITE, MOFRO and THE BLACK KEYS this ia an old-school rootsadelic roadshow not to be missed... |Check out the band.

column14:
THE FIRST TWO SEGMENTS OF THIS EVENT ARE NOW SOLD OUT. We have shut down registration. But you can still come to the after party in the bier garten after 6pm. Scroll down for info and come on over!

Come learn how to find your next best customer, network, have an appetizer and a drink or two - try out some new tools, apps designed to make your life easier. Oh, and there's a party too. All free. No expensive badges required. But you do need a ticket to get in so register here - and maybe invite a friend. :)
2PM PRESENTATION & PANELS

PANEL: Local Leaders You Need To Know
Rosy Jalifi, Asst Director, City of Austin Small Business Division
Rebecca Melancon, Exec Dir, Austin Independent Business Alliance
Eve Richter, Partner at Napkin Ventures and VP at Door64
PRESENTATION: Be Local, Think Global, Go Mobile
Constant Contact's Director of Field Education & Development Julie Niehoff will present a brief talk on driving engagement, more referrals and repeat business.

PANEL: Get More Exposure, More Media, More Likes & Shares
- Lani Rosales, COO of AGBeat.com
- Erica Ayotte, Social Media Manager for Constant Contact, Inc.
- Deb Pfitzenmeier, Editor of SABusyKids.com


4PM APPS & APPS
Network Over Drinks, Appetizers & Some Really Cool Tools
We'll bust out tasty appetizers, beer and wine and invite you to mingle. Some of our favorite software partners will setup to show you their apps --tools to grow your list, sell your stuff, schedule your time more efficiently, run a contest, do more with less. Who doesn't want that?

Note - If you're a techie: This is your chance to meet developers that have integrated with us, learn about tools that are integrated with Constant Contact, and find out how to become an AppConnect partner. Basically, talk tech.


6PM HAPPY HOUR - Stay for the Party!
We'll move to the outdoor beer garten, start live music from Sun Salutation, Jamfoot and UK group We Steal Flyers! We'll open a cash bar and you can party or network into the night. This is our appreciation party for Constant Contact customers & partners. (BUT you're invited even if you don't use our tools!) No expensive badges required and parking is free, but you need to register to attend - you'll get a ticket to enter. You can register for up to 5 people.

The Social Media Monthly is excited and proud to present our first organized side event at #SXSW.
This will be our third year exhibiting at SXSW,
and we're looking forward to contributing to the fun and flavor at SXSW.

In association with our lead sponsor, R2i, and our partner at SXSW, NakedWines, we'll be presenting SXSW's largest wine tasting event the evening of the first day of the tradeshow, March 10th from 6pm-10pm at the Karma Lounge at 105 East 5th Street, just 2 blocks from the convention center.

Courtesy of NakedWines,
every attendee of the event will receive a $50 gift card redeemable on NakedWines.com.

This is an official SXSW event, but badges are not required to attend or participate.|We supply the caffeine, snacks, T-shirts, prizes and some professional guidance.|You bring a Wi-Fi-enabled computer – and then you bring it. column14:
You're invited to join us on Friday, March 8 at HackATX, an all-night hackathon hosted by T3, 7-Eleven and ARC. This is an official SXSW event, but badges are not required to attend or participate.
We supply the caffeine, snacks, T-shirts, prizes and some professional guidance.
You bring a Wi-Fi-enabled computer – and then you bring it. We believe in fearless collaboration and think you should too. HackATX encourages building a robust team of programmers, UX practitioners and creatives.
It all starts at 6 p.m. with a kick-off party at T3 Headquarters featuring beer and local bands Shane Smith, Pangia and Seaholm Electric. Coding begins at 8 p.m. and ends at 8 a.m. Saturday morning, followed by presentations. Hackers are welcome to stay the night at T3 or work virtually. Teams will be given access to a suite of 7-Eleven APIs developed by T3 to use. The winner will be selected by a panel of industry-leading judges based on a combination of functionality, design and presentation.
Bragging rights are on the line – and cold, hard cash.
Winners Receive:
1st place: $3,000
2nd place: $1,500
3rd place: $500
Think you can hack it? Then we hope to see you there.
Please enter a separate email address for each attendee.
For questions, please contact Natalie Reichstein at natalie.reichstein@t-3.com.

column14:
What a perfect fit! Have a couple of beers and find our how to help Austin area dogs in need! Dogs and brews and live tunes! This March, Blue Dog Rescue of Austin, TX and Lagunitas Brewing Company (Petaluma, Calif.) will bring bands from the headwaters of Sonoma County to Opal's Freehouse during the famed South by Southwest Music Conference to help speak for the dogs!


The "Sonoma Grown" Showcase will be presented at Opal Divine's Freehouse benefiting Blue Dog Rescue. In addition to sponsoring the showcases, Lagunitas Brewing Company El Presidente, Tony Magee will be in attendance and playing finger pickin' blues from the 20's and 30's. Not only will folks learn about cool ways to help in Austin's animal rescue scene, but also rock to great Sonoma County bands, and meet the owner of Lagunitas, who's been brewing craft beers since '93. Come on by, we'll be tappin' special kegs, tappin' our feet, and howlin' at the wind..

8:30pm
Northside Southpaws (Roots/Chicago)
10pm

"Blue Dog Rescue is honored to be part of the Lagunitas Brewing Company music showcases during this year's SXSW. Tony and the folks at Lagunitas are longtime supporters of animal charities and we're proud they have asked Blue Dog Rescue to be part of their time right here in Austin, Texas."

column2: Saustex Records Showcase Night One
column12: Ol' Yeller,Rice Moorehead Band,El Pathos,Dickie Lee Erwin Band,The Cry Babies,Victor Olston
column13: Saustex is happy to present some rootsy madness by our friends from around the Western World on Thursday March 14th at Opal Divine's Freehouse. Kicking the evening off will be Shreveport, LA based Victor Olston, featuring Alabama Shakes organist Ben Jones. 8pm brings the Dickie Lee Erwin Band with many of my favorite Austin vet musicians. Saustex artists El Pathos hit it next in their recently unveiled unplugged edition. All the way from Berlin come The Cry Babies to rock the house. Rice Moorehead & His Ladies will show everyone why two drum sets are better than one. From the North Country of Minnesota come Ol' Yeller to finish out the night. This event is free and open to the public.

column14:
PORTLANDIA BANDS OCCUPY AUSTIN MARCH 13TH FOR SECOND ANNUAL PORTLAND PARTY


Last year was the inaugural year for the first annual Portland Party at SXSW, an unofficial showcase highlighting over 20 artists from Portland, Oregon. With a turnout in the thousands and some of the best music from the Pacific Northwest, the 2012 Portland Party was a huge success. This year, the Portlanders are going even bigger.


The 2013 Portland Party takes place on Wednesday, March 13th at The Grackle in Austin from 12:00pm until 2:00am. The Party will feature 27 bands from Portland, including: Sallie Ford & The Sound Outside, who was featured on David Letterman in 2011 and released their latest album “Untamed Beast” on February 19, 2013; Battleme, a featured artist on Sons of Anarchy; Radiation City, named Portland’s Best New Band for 2012 by the Willamette Week and one of NPR’s 2013 Artists to Watch; and Brainstorm, who just released Heat Waves to national acclaim. A full list of all 27 bands is included below.


The Portland Party will host its arsenal of bands on 2 main stages during all hours of the day on March 13th. The Portland Party wouldn’t be complete without FREE BOOZE. From 3:00-4:00pm, attendees can enjoy free beer for one hour from Brooklyn Brewery in the Portland Party Power Hour. For those more interested in the finer things in life should join the Party from 6:00-7:00pm for Wine Time, an hour of free wine brought to Austin from the great Northwest winery, A to Z Wineworks.

In addition, there is quite the pool party this year on site. Attendees are encouraged to bring their bathing suits and take a dip while checking out an outdoor poolside acoustic stage and an underwater photo booth. Pool partiers will be assisted by our friends at GoPro, who will be on site to set up some GoPro cameras and show folks how to use them for fun, underwater photo shoots. Poolside music and the underwater photo booth run from 1pm-6pm.


The 2013 Portland Party bands: Sallie Ford & The Sound Outside, Radiation City, Battleme, Brainstorm, Sean Flinn & The Royal We, The Chicharones, Sapient, Rags & Ribbons, Wild Ones, Tango Alpha Tango, Quiet Life, Animal Eyes, The Shivas, Shook Twins, Seacats, Water Tower, Nick Jaina, Rare Monk, Bike Thief, Natasha Kmeto, Southerly, Vikesh Kapoor, McDougall, Dual Mode, and Hip Hatchet.

The 2013 Portland Party is presented by A to Z Wineworks, Voodoo Doughnut, Tender Loving Empire, Portland Mercury, Octopus Entertainment, Marmoset, and Eleven Magazine. More information on the Portland Party can be found online at www.sxswportlandparty.com.


Media Contact - Will Sherman

wsherman@wavemakergroup.com | 512.584.9990

column2: PwC Advisory - Social Business Presents Official SXSW Internet of Things Meetup - Man Meet Machine (Badges Required)
column13: This meetup will focus on how connected devices from our smartphones to our cars and even medical devices are transforming the way we live and work. Whether it’s for personal devices, a social network, a humanitarian effort or for business resource optimization, a key characteristic of the Internet of Things is its massive scale and self-organizing nature. As sensor prices drop and cloud makes sharing data across the Internet increasing easy, smart devices are getting woven into the fabric of our daily lives and enabling global connectedness and the opportunity for new technologies to make everyone's lives better. The Internet of Things is connecting us all, so we should connect in person to discuss where this is all headed. All entrepreneurs, developers, data professionals, technologists, scientists, the DIY community, Web community managers and anyone else who is excited about the Internet of Things should join us for this session.|Speakers/Meetup Host: Kat Mandelstein|Customer Impact, Social Business PwC Advisory|Kat Mandelstein recently joined PwC Advisory through the integration of Ant's Eye View as the Director of Social Business. She also serves on the International Board of Directors for Social Media Club and served as the President of the local Austin Chapter. Previously Kat was an executive in IBM Software Group and led a number demand program, digital marketing and development teams over the years. Kat has been a regular contributor to the Austinot, BtoB Magazine’s BtoBlog and The Beancast. Kat managed one of the earliest successful retail Web sites, www.jcpenney.com. Kat holds a B.S. in Advertising with Minor in Marketing from the University of Texas at Austin and a Global Leadership MBA from the University of Texas at Dallas.You can find her on Twitter: @katmandelstein@SMCAustin @SocialMediaClub

column2: Fast Company Happy Hour (Day One)
column13: Fast Company, in association with the BMF Media Group, will host the Fast Company Grill in Austin, Texas from March 8-12, 2013. The FastCompany Grill will feature an exclusive five-day restaurant, lounge, and arcade exclusive to artists, celebrities, media, VIPs and tastemakers. The Fast Company Grill will showcase exciting interactive activities daily from sponsors Lincoln, Target, Starbucks Doubleshot, and Evite. Through the selection of key Austin partners, The Lincoln Hello, Again experience will re-imagine the space into a blend of the city, through gaming and interactive technology. FastCompany will be interviewing top business, technology and media executives including Jonah Peretti, Jared Leto, Kevin Rose, Dennis Crowley, Troy Carter, Doug Ulman and Padma Warrior for its “Creative Conversations” video series. Fast Company aims to reveal the inner thoughts and ideas of unlikely business pairings as they share how they innovate and re-imagine their companies, products, media and technology with one another. Target and Fast Company are celebrating their first-ever partnership at the Fast Company Grill with four dedicated Happy Hours featuring notable co-hosts Cultivated Wit with Baratunde Thurston and Girls In Tech, along with a special performance by Glenn Tilbrook of Squeeze on Friday. Target is transforming a section of the Fast Company Grill to a “Tarcade” with refurbished retro video games, Minneapolis inspired cocktails, NFC Tarcade cards, and opportunities for guests to challenge each other throughout the week.

column14:
RxSM Self Medicated Film Expo & South Texas Underground Film are pleased to announce

The Self Medicated 24hr Film Challenge

Saturday March 9th - Sunday March 10th (10am - 10am)



Online Registration starts March 3rd.


Kick-off starts at 10am, March 9th, 2013 online and at Emo’s Plaza in Austin, Tx. Turn-in will be online March 10 at 10am with the team uploading their film on Youtube and sending their link through email.


Films will be collected and streamed on RxSM’s YouTube Channel. Online Screening and audience voting will begin March 10th - March 31st.


Award winners will be announced at the Victoria TX Indie Film Festival in Victoria, Tx April 4th - 7th. Top 3 films and Audience Award Winners will receive badges to the Victoria TX Indie Film Festival (Victoria, Tx) and to the South Texas Underground Film Festival (STUFF 2013) Oct. 3rd - 6th 2013 (Corpus Christi, Tx) and will be screened at both festivals.


Films will be graded on time, elements and creativity. Filmmakers have 24 hours to write, film and edit a short film. Assigned elements will be drawn and emailed to the team leaders and posted online.

column14:
NOTE: like most SXSW parties, RSVP doesn't guarantee entry. Please arrive early. Flula will be performing just after 1pm.

YouTube personality and German techno DJ Flula Borg performs his songs at the Sonos Studio @ SXSW. Lunch, drinks, music and Flula... in your face!

DJ Flula Borg, Techno DJ,YouTube star, savant, German, and wild animal aficionado will be hosting an afternoon of fun and frivolity at the Sonos Studio during SXSW Interactive, powered by POP-AUT.

Come have a drink and find out why German’s can’t pronounce the word “squirrel.” Flula will be performing hits like “Dirk Nowitzki: German Moses,” and spinning his favorite 90s jams.

In support Flula Borg's recent obsession with "Flair" (see video below), POP-AUT is harnessing the power of the YouTube API to dynamically turn uncommon YouTube Channel statistics into "Video Flair." This pre-beta release of POP-AUT gives insight to channel owners to learn more about how their videos are performing on YouTube.

w/ DJ Ivory Tower

Get your flair and see how POP-AUT can power your creativity at: http://POP-AUT.com. Get your Flula at: http://flula.de

via eventbrite

column14:
Let us help you fight that mid-week SXSW slump that you may be experiencing due to late night parties, early morning activities, and mid day, well, parties again!

A short yoga class will start at 9:15am led by the an amazing instructor from the iGnite team. BYO mat, or we have them here for your purchasing pleasure too!

Post class we will have a Bloody Mary bar, yes, we know you need a kick in the pants to start off your day with some adult beverages.

Oh, wait, it's SXSW isn't it... There will be LIVE music durning the short and restorative yoga class. Then stick around to enjoy live tunes while sippin on those drinks, gearing up for the next round of SXSW parties we all know you already have planned, or just come in and enjoy the perks of the week without having to get into the madness of downtown!

Let's Recap:
9:00am doors
9:15am Yoga starts (you don't have to be any good, we love all yall)
10:00am LIVE MUSIC, Drinks, snacks

column2: The Bounceback After Party
column13: We hope you will be able to join Bryan Poyser and the cast at the after party following the premiere of THE BOUNCEBACK.|Saturday, March 9thLocation: The Gibson Room @ Maggie Mae's (323 E 6th Street)4:30pm-6:30pmRSVP to gerilyn@brigademarketing.com|Breaking up is hard to do. Being hopelessly in love and trying to endure a bros weekend in the same city as your ex makes it even harder. Desperate and lonely, when Stan (Michael Stahl-David) learns that his ex, Cathy (Ashley Bell), will be in Austin for the weekend, he hops on the first flight to the Lone Star State in hopes of “accidentally” running into her there. Little does he know that another breakup crisis will greet him in Austin between his friends Jeff (Zach Cregger) and Kara (Sara Paxton), who are hell-bent on keeping Stan and Cathy apart. Cavorting through Austin’s honkytonks, nightclubs, and a cutthroat air-sex competition featuring Jeff and his debaucherous new buddies, the two couples find bouncing back from heartache to be unexpectedly complicated. An outrageous and heartfelt comedy, THE BOUNCEBACK is Bryan Poyser's follow-up to the hit Sundance film, LOVERS OF HATE.
column14:
We hope you will be able to join Bryan Poyser and the cast at the after party following the premiere of THE BOUNCEBACK.


Saturday, March 9th

Location: The Gibson Room @ Maggie Mae's (323 E 6th Street)

4:30pm-6:30pm

RSVP to gerilyn@brigademarketing.com

Breaking up is hard to do. Being hopelessly in love and trying to endure a bros weekend in the same city as your ex makes it even harder. Desperate and lonely, when Stan (Michael Stahl-David) learns that his ex, Cathy (Ashley Bell), will be in Austin for the weekend, he hops on the first flight to the Lone Star State in hopes of “accidentally” running into her there. Little does he know that another breakup crisis will greet him in Austin between his friends Jeff (Zach Cregger) and Kara (Sara Paxton), who are hell-bent on keeping Stan and Cathy apart. Cavorting through Austin’s honkytonks, nightclubs, and a cutthroat air-sex competition featuring Jeff and his debaucherous new buddies, the two couples find bouncing back from heartache to be unexpectedly complicated. An outrageous and heartfelt comedy, THE BOUNCEBACK is Bryan Poyser's follow-up to the hit Sundance film, LOVERS OF HATE.

column2: Virgin Mobile House (Day One) - RSVP required!
column13: For the last 3 years, the Virgin Mobile House has earned the reputation as the premiere after-hours “hang” for SXSW insiders. The VM House serves as a central hub delivering access to tomorrow’s game changing bands to industry glitterati & music lovers alike in a laid back and electric environment.|Historically the VM House activation at SXSW Music has been a well-attended staple in the Austin landscape. The 2013 SXSW season will be no different with the VM House hosting a vast array of killer bands and DJ sets taking over the entire site with performances both indoors & outdoors well into the small hours of the night from March 13-16, 2013. |RSVP now for you and one guest to attend the 2013 Virgin Mobile House.|via virginmobile
column14:
For the last 3 years, the Virgin Mobile House has earned the reputation as the premiere after-hours “hang” for SXSW insiders. The VM House serves as a central hub delivering access to tomorrow’s game changing bands to industry glitterati & music lovers alike in a laid back and electric environment.
Historically the VM House activation at SXSW Music has been a well-attended staple in the Austin landscape. The 2013 SXSW season will be no different with the VM House hosting a vast array of killer bands and DJ sets taking over the entire site with performances both indoors & outdoors well into the small hours of the night from March 13-16, 2013.

RSVP now for you and one guest to attend the 2013 Virgin Mobile House.

via virginmobile

column14:
Performance art is a form of expression that is concerned more with content, context, and concept than audience expectations and entertainment value. Performance art can be laboriously scripted or spastically random. Performance art is at the same time the highest, purest, and most liberating form of art while being it's most constricting, confusing, and convoluted. Designed to be equally challenging to both performer and viewer, performance art is set in the mediums of time, space, and audience gaze.

Still not sure what Performance art is? Come out and find out.

Artists pooled from the Visual, Dance, Experimental music, and Performance communities of Austin's thriving art scene, are going to put their definitions of Performance art to the test only an audience can provide. Each artist is given 15 minutes of time to conceive, conceal, converge, and conclude. Come be a part of it.

This time we are going to be at 29th Street Ballroom!

column14:
High-Fives at High Noon (quoting nickcicero)

Meet Community Managers From Around the World at the First Annual Community Manager High-Five FlashMob at SXSW



Flash Mob Details:

  1. Act casual before the event, just chill. Ya know, pretend you're checking your Twitter feed, taking an important call for a C-level exec, reading an important article in the local newspaper, or removing lint from your sweater.
  2. Then, exactly at noon, massive High-Fives and glorious community manager roaring! (roar!) Make a scene (all legally of course). SuperBatMan High-Five like you won the Superbowl/Lottery/Oscar/Scoble kissed you, all in the same day!

  3. Get to know folks, solidify those online relationships, now in real life!

  4. HashTag #CMAD your pics!

  5. After 15 minutes, FlashMob go Boom! We disperse, and go to events as a crew.



Where:

  • On the Intersection of Trinity and Fourth near the Convention Center


When:

  • Sat at Noon, March 9 (but come a few minutes early to get ready)
  • It's only 15 minutes long!


Who:

  • Community Managers
  • Community Manager Apprecianados
  • Friends of Community Managers (FOCM)
  • High-Five Committee Members
  • High-Five Beta Testers|


Cost:
  • Entry Fee: High-Fives!
  • Materials Fee: High-Fives!
  • Exit Fee: High-Fives!

Why:

  • Meet and Greet those you interact with on a frequent basis, but now in the flesh.
  • Community Managers help people online and make them feel awesome. Let's do it Live. Do it Live! cc Bill OReilly.
  • New to High-Fives? Linky Link: Here's a Five Step Plan.

column2: Austin Social Affair: SX Wine-Down
column13: You’re invited to Austin Social Affair’s first bi-annual wine tasting competition! This is a relaxed wine tasting event where the bottle's labels are hidden. You and your team bring in your favorite wine, enter it into the competition and the tastings begin! Vote for your top four favorites and your least favorite during the tasting hours. Winners will be announced at the end of the event and get to go home with cases of wine! |via facebook

column2: Duma Taiwan
column13: Are you tired of the same old recycled label-dependent music? If so, Join us for Duma Taiwan at SXSW 2013 an official SXSW party, for all international folks heading to Austin. Some of Taiwan’s hottest up and coming talent bands will be performing at the Duma Taiwan, showcasing 3 very different music styles and a ton of potential. Come with Duma (black bear in Taiwan’s aboriginal language). It’s your only chance to explore one of the world’s best lifestyles without going the distance!

column2: Capital Factory Presents: Advances in Innovation in DC - Google+ Hangout 2 Panel Event
column13: Join us March 9th as we talk to Senator Moran, Senator Warner, Congressman Issa and others in Austin and discuss advances in innovation in DC! Agenda: Part 1: High Growth Entrepreneurship with a Focus on Access to Capital Time: 12:00pm -12:30pm Topic: Startup Act 3.0 Speakers: • U.S. Senator Jerry Moran (R-KS), co-author of the Startup Act 3.0 • U.S. Senator Mark Warner (D-VA), co-author of the Startup Act 3.0 Moderator: Jamie Rhodes, Chair of the Alliance of Texas Angel Networks (ATAN), Vice Chair for the national Angel Capital Association, co-founder of National Nanomaterials Inc. Part 2: Access to Global Talent & Tech’s Critical New Leadership Time: 12:40pm - 1:30pm Topics: High-Skilled Immigration: Startup Act 3.0 & The Startup Visa Act; SOPA takeaways and the virtual March for Innovation, April 2013 Speakers: • U.S. Senator Mark Warner (D-VA) cosponsor of Startup Visa Act in the 110th, 111th, and 113th Congresses • U.S. Congressman Darrell Issa (R-CA 49), Chair of the House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform • Jeremy Robbins, Director, Partnership for a New American Economy; Policy Advisor and Special Counsel in the Office of New York Mayor Michael R. Bloomberg • Michael McGeary, Co-founder and Executive Director, Engine Advocacy Moderators: Mitch Jacobson, Director of the Clean Energy Incubator, Austin Technology Incubator (ATI) & Erika Sumner, Innovation Advocate
column14:
Join us March 9th as we talk to Senator Moran, Senator Warner, Congressman Issa and others in Austin and discuss advances in innovation in DC!

Agenda:

Part 1: High Growth Entrepreneurship with a Focus on Access to Capital

Time: 12:00pm -12:30pm

Topic: Startup Act 3.0

Speakers:

• U.S. Senator Jerry Moran (R-KS), co-author of the Startup Act 3.0

• U.S. Senator Mark Warner (D-VA), co-author of the Startup Act 3.0

Moderator: Jamie Rhodes, Chair of the Alliance of Texas Angel Networks (ATAN), Vice Chair for the national Angel Capital Association, co-founder of National Nanomaterials Inc.

Part 2: Access to Global Talent & Tech’s Critical New Leadership

Time: 12:40pm - 1:30pm

Topics: High-Skilled Immigration: Startup Act 3.0 & The Startup Visa Act; SOPA takeaways and the virtual March for Innovation, April 2013

Speakers:

• U.S. Senator Mark Warner (D-VA) cosponsor of Startup Visa Act in the 110th, 111th, and 113th Congresses

• U.S. Congressman Darrell Issa (R-CA 49), Chair of the House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform

• Jeremy Robbins, Director, Partnership for a New American Economy; Policy Advisor and Special Counsel in the Office of New York Mayor Michael R. Bloomberg

• Michael McGeary, Co-founder and Executive Director, Engine Advocacy

Moderators: Mitch Jacobson, Director of the Clean Energy Incubator, Austin Technology Incubator (ATI) & Erika Sumner, Innovation Advocate

column2: CanWeNetwork 2013 Unofficial SXSW Network Bus
column13: The CanWeNetwork bus is rolling into its second year at SXSW! Guerlain perfumes have a distinctive and timeless high-quality because of a prevalent vanilla and amber accord in many their fragrances. This one of a kind attribute is referred to as the 'Guerlinade'. Christian Dior was born in 1905 within a comfortable household. In 1955 he hires as his assistant Yves Sain-Laurent who will continue his work just after his death in 1957. These days the corporation is run by Gianfranco Ferre e John Galliano. Lancome is actually a French cosmetic enterprise founded by Armand Petitjean (1884-1970) in 1935. His brand was 'born in the days when trendy French girls nevertheless wore gloves and did not possess the appropriate to vote' as Time International mentions. He began his enterprise by launching five fragarnces: 'Tendre Nuit', 'Bocages', 'Conquette', 'Kypre' and 'Tropique' at the World's Fair in Brussels, Belgium. The name of Lancome derives from the name of the Chateau de Lancosme. As some say his fondness for roses or for the wild roses surrounding that Chateau (Castle) convinced him to pick out a golden rose as enterprise symbol. Lancome perfumes contain Trésor, Trésor in Really like, Magnifique, Poème, Magie Noire, Miracle, but probably probably the most popular could be the Lancome Hypnose collection. Lancome has been owned by L'Oréal considering the fact that 1964. Designer and fragrance maker Hubert James Taffin de Givenchy was born in Beauvais, France in 1927. He began as a style designer and had two lovely ladies as models Audrey Hepburn and Jackie Kennedy. Opened the Givenchy House in 1952. His name became well-liked also as a fragrance maker for women and men. Starting with Givenchy in 1959 the men perfumes created a massive step ahead with Givenchy Gentleman in 1975, Xeryus in '80s, and Pi in '90s. Extra lately - Givenchy Pour Homme, Givenchy Blue Label, and Very Irresistible Givenchy pour Homme. Givenchy perfumes include things like also Ysatis, launched in 1984, then Amarige in 1991, and Organza in 1996. In 2003 he launches Really Irresistible Givenchy - a fruity-floral fragrance. Band performances start Wednesday, March 13 from 3 to 8pm, and they will include; Poolside, Robert Delong, Sir Sly, Thomas Dybdahl, Chali 2Na, Kitten, and Robert Glasper.


SXSW badgeholders get priority access to the Sonos Studio, located directly behind the Convention Center at 608 Third Street, and it is open to the public during the day until it reaches capacity.

KCRW continues to redefine what radio means in a world of evolving technology.

KCRW is also sponsoring Filter Magazine’s Showdown at Cedar Street showcases, which are open to the public. RSVP here and make sure to arrive early.

column2: Band Can Resolve Diabetes Hypertension
column13: The Lap-Band can be a secure and productive strategy of fat reduction surgery, intended to help those sufferers that have involving 50 - one hundred pounds to shed. The Lap-Band limits food intake, and paired with healthy life style alterations, allows patients to cease struggling with their weight problems. Lap-Band surgery that is performed laparoscopically makes it possible for individuals to commit less than 24 hours within the hospital, ordinarily. Individuals can expect to return to perform inside per week, and can resume exercise inside a month to six weeks. If you can find surgical complications, recovery may possibly take slightly longer. Persons normally ask just how much weight they are going to lose using the Lap-Band. Fat reduction final results vary from patient to patient, and is dependent on a number of aspects. The Lap-Band has to be in the appropriate position, plus the patient have to be committed to generating life style changes, and enhancing eating habits. Fat loss may be as a great deal as two to 3 pounds per week, but the average is about a pound a week. About 18 months after Lap-Band surgery individuals can anticipate their weight reduction Bear in mind, the aim of your Lap-Band is just not to knowledge dramatic weight-loss quickly, as there are lots of wellness risks linked with rapid fat loss. The greatest benefit for the Lap-Band might be the resolution of well being challenges like diabetes and hypertension that typically create because of obesity. The web is a good spot to acquire facts, but it also can be a location where you can find lots of myths propagated. The Lap-band is no exception. Here are some of my favorites: (a) You cannot drink coffee together with the band. False. You are able to drink coffee or tea with the band. We don't want you to drink lots of liquid calories, so avoid these high calorie Starbuck's drinks. In our recovery space, we give our sufferers either tea or coffee. (b) The band should be tight adequate to stop you from eating a lot of meals. False. The Lap-Band band will not operate by "restriction," it performs by "suppression" of appetite. Food goes via the band in about a minute - so you are able to consume as a great deal as you ate ahead of. Your job should be to limit what you consume, and the Lap-Band makes it so you won't be hungry before the following meal. (c) The Lap-Band causes reflux and heartburn. False. The band can be a barrier against reflux, heartburn, and evening cough. For those who develop any of those, then you definitely have also tight a band, or have created a band slip. Anytime you get reflux or heartburn get in touch with your surgeon immediately.If you like balenciaga please Visit our balenciaga city bag! Happy shopping!
